---

<ContentApp
  title="How PAI works"
  description="How PAI works: amnesic live USB, offline AI, hardened networking, and free software — explained."
>
  <nav slot="sidebar">
    <p class="sb-brand">How PAI works</p>
    {sections.map((s) => <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="sb-link">{s.label}</a>)}
    <hr class="sb-divider" />
    <a href="/apps/about" class="sb-link" style="font-size:0.8125rem">About PAI →</a>
    <a href="/apps/security" class="sb-link" style="font-size:0.8125rem">Security model →</a>
    <a href="/apps/flash" class="sb-link" style="font-size:0.8125rem">Download PAI →</a>
  </nav>

  <h1>How PAI works</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    PAI is a bootable USB operating system that turns any x86-64 computer into a private AI
    workstation — offline, amnesic, and leaving nothing behind.
  </p>

  <!-- ──────────────────────────────────────────── Pillar 1 -->
  <h2 class="pillar">Leave no trace on the computer</h2>

  <section id="leave-no-trace">
    <h3>Your private AI workstation, anywhere</h3>
    <p>
      To use PAI, shut down the computer and start it from your PAI USB stick instead of booting
      Windows, macOS, or Linux. You can temporarily turn any computer into a private AI machine, or
      safely use a computer that isn't yours.
    </p>
    <p>
      PAI is a ~2 GB download and takes a few minutes to flash. It boots on most x86-64 machines
      made in the last ten years and runs entirely in RAM. You can start again on the host operating
      system after shutting PAI down.
    </p>
    <p>
      You don't have to worry about the host having viruses, because PAI runs independently from
      the installed operating system and never uses the internal hard disk. PAI cannot, however,
      protect you if you install it from a compromised computer, or if the hardware itself is
      malicious (for example a hardware keylogger).
    </p>
    <ul class="see-also">
      <li><a href="/apps/security">Warnings: PAI is safe but not magic</a></li>
      <li><a href="/apps/flash">Download and flash PAI</a></li>
      <li><a href="/apps/hardware">System requirements and recommended hardware</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="amnesia">
    <h3>Amnesia</h3>
    <p>
      PAI always starts from the same clean state, and <strong>everything you do disappears
      automatically when you shut down PAI</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>Without PAI, almost everything you do on a computer leaves traces:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Chat prompts and AI responses, saved in cloud history</li>
      <li>Files you opened or created, even after you deleted them</li>
      <li>Passwords, even if you use a password manager</li>
      <li>Every device and Wi-Fi network you connected to</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      PAI never writes anything to the host hard disk and only runs from the memory of the computer.
      Memory is fully cleared when you shut down, erasing all possible traces — including AI
      conversations, which exist only in RAM while PAI is running.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="persistence">
    <h3>Encrypted persistence (opt-in)</h3>
    <p>
      You can choose to save some of your files and configuration to an encrypted partition on the
      USB stick: your AI model weights, chat history, SSH keys, Wi-Fi passwords, wallets, and
      additional software. The persistent partition is optional, LUKS2-encrypted, and you always
      decide what is persistent — everything else stays amnesic.
    </p>
    <ul class="see-also">
      <li><a href="/apps/docs">Set up encrypted persistence</a></li>
      <li><a href="/apps/docs">Install additional software</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ──────────────────────────────────────────── Pillar 2 -->
  <h2 class="pillar">Private AI, offline</h2>

  <section id="private-ai">
    <h3>Local models, no cloud</h3>
    <p>
      Every major AI service — ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini — sends your prompts to remote servers where
      you have no control over who reads them, how long they are stored, or who they are shared
      with.
    </p>
    <p>
      PAI eliminates that trust chain. All inference happens locally via
      <a href="https://ollama.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ollama</a>, which runs
      Llama, Mistral, Phi, Gemma, and 100+ other open-weight models entirely on your hardware. No
      API keys, no accounts, no prompts leaving the machine.
    </p>
    <p>
      The built-in Chat app talks to Ollama over localhost only. The firewall blocks every inbound
      connection, and Ollama is not reachable from the network. When you shut PAI down, the model
      is unloaded from RAM along with every conversation you had with it.
    </p>
    <ul class="see-also">
      <li><a href="/apps/chat">Try the Chat app</a></li>
      <li><a href="/apps/docs">Download and run models with Ollama</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ──────────────────────────────────────────── Pillar 3 -->
  <h2 class="pillar">Leave no trace on the network</h2>

  <section id="hardened-network">
    <h3>Hardened by default</h3>
    <p>
      PAI ships with a restrictive default posture. Your network identity and outbound traffic are
      protected by several layers you don't have to configure:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>MAC address randomized on every boot</strong> — the host machine presents a fresh
        hardware identity each session, so Wi-Fi operators can't link you across visits.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>UFW firewall, default-deny inbound</strong> — nothing on the local network can reach
        services running on PAI, including Ollama and the PAI UI.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No telemetry, no analytics, no auto-updates phoning home</strong> — PAI does not
        make a single network call unless you initiate it.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Tor for everything (opt-in)</h3>
    <p>
      Run <code>sudo pai-privacy on</code> and all outbound traffic — including DNS — is routed
      through the Tor network. This hides your IP from whatever server you're talking to, and hides
      what you're doing on the network from your ISP or local observer.
    </p>
    <p>
      Unlike Tails, PAI does not force Tor by default. PAI's focus is <em>private AI</em>, and most
      AI inference never needs the network at all. Tor is one command away when you do need it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ──────────────────────────────────────────── Pillar 4 -->
  <h2 class="pillar">A full workstation</h2>

  <section id="digital-toolbox">
    <h3>Digital toolbox</h3>
    <p>
      PAI includes a curated selection of applications to work on sensitive material and communicate
      securely — ready to use and configured with safe defaults:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Chat</strong> — local LLM chat UI, talks to Ollama over localhost only</li>
      <li><strong>Ollama</strong> — run and manage 100+ open-weight models offline</li>
      <li><strong>Firefox ESR</strong> — with uBlock Origin and hardened defaults</li>
      <li><strong>Terminal (foot)</strong> — zsh, tmux, and common dev tools pre-installed</li>
      <li><strong>Electrum & Monero wallets</strong> — pre-configured with sane privacy defaults</li>
      <li><strong>Sway + Waybar</strong> — a keyboard-first Wayland tiling desktop</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Applications that try to reach the internet without going through Tor are blocked when
      Tor-only mode is on. The firewall enforces the policy; individual apps cannot opt out.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ──────────────────────────────────────────── Pillar 5 -->
  <h2 class="pillar">Software for freedom</h2>

  <section id="free-software">
    <h3>Transparency to build trust</h3>
    <p>
      All the source code, build scripts, and configuration for PAI is public, so independent
      researchers can verify that PAI really works the way we say it does. PAI is built on Debian
      12, which itself is scrutinized by a global community of maintainers.
    </p>
    <p>
      PAI is released under the <strong>GNU General Public License v3.0</strong>. You can audit the
      code, modify it, redistribute it, or fork the whole project.
    </p>
    <ul class="see-also">
      <li>
        <a href="https://github.com/nirholas/pai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          Source code on GitHub ↗
        </a>
      </li>
      <li><a href="/apps/verify">Verify your ISO against signed checksums</a></li>
      <li><a href="/apps/security">Full security model and threat model</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="top-security-free">
    <h3>Top security for free</h3>
    <p>
      Nobody should have to pay to use AI privately. PAI is free software, free to download, and
      free to share. It is built and maintained by volunteers; if you want to help, contribute
      code, documentation, translations, or a donation on GitHub.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <button class="btn btn--primary" data-open-app="Flash">Download PAI</button>
      <a href="/apps/about" class="btn">About PAI</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/nirholas/pai" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >View on GitHub ↗</a
      >
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentApp>

